cleaned_message: Alright I'll give a list of the biggest things I've noticed: - seed oils are as bad if not worse for you than sugar, stick to butter/tallow/coconut/olive oil as fats when you're eating - saturated fat and cholesterol aren't bad for you as long as you're at a healthy body weight, in fact they're needed for proper hormone production - most people are deficient in magnesium, supplement it or make sure you're getting a lot in your diet (it's depleted in most of the soil in America, so keep in mind most food has a lot less than it says on the label) - organ meats are a natural multivitamin, especially beef liver. Try to eat these at least once a week - brown rice doesn't actually have much more nutrients than white, and is harder to digest. Stick to white rice, especially since it tastes better. - the standard American diet is so bad that almost ANY other diet will lead to better health. This doesn't specifically mean a veggie/vegan diet is healthy, just better than eating McDonald's - 1g/lb of bodyweight protein if you lift, .5g/lb for general health - your body burns carbs before fat, and fat before protein - fiber has no calories, but is pretty filling, so eating more fiber (from veggies and fruit) can help you lose weight - sugar in fruits is bound in cells that are slow to digest, making it release slowly into the body rather than all at once like processed foods. Juice/smoothies or anything that breaks the cells down releases the sugar, and makes it hit the body like refined sugars - hydrogenated oils are poison, never eat these in any scenario. Common sources are margarine, vegetable shortening and processed peanut butter - a lot of plant foods have inflammatory chemicals, antinutrients and hormones as a defence mechanism. Soy is the best example of this, but a lot of grains and vegetables have them too. Learn to properly cook/process plant foods to remove these toxins.
